<div class="content">
<h1 id='overview'>Overview</h1>
<p>This documentation describes various ways to access Printify services by using the Printify API. Each section has a
detailed description as well as code examples to help you easily start creating products and fulfilling orders. </p>
<h2 id='api-usage-guidelines'>API Usage Guidelines</h2>
<p>All integrations must comply with the Printify Terms and Printify API Terms. Please see these pages for more details:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="https://printify.com/terms-of-service/">https://printify.com/terms-of-service/</a></li>
<li><a href="https://printify.com/API-terms/">https://printify.com/API-terms/</a></li>
</ul>

<p>The Printify public endpoints are powered by the same underlying technology that powers the core Printify Platform. As a
result, Printify engineering closely monitors usage of the public APIs to ensure a quality experience for users of the
Printify platform.
Below, you&#39;ll find the limits by which a single integration (identified per account and not per access token) can
consume the Printify APIs. If you have any questions, please <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/requests/new?ticket_form_id=4421334895377">create a support ticket</a> by selecting one of the topics on the support page and indicating &quot;API&quot; as the option chosen under &quot;Channels&quot;. Please add more information to provide full details and we will contact you shortly.</p>

<p>Printify has the following global limit in place for API requests:</p>

<ul>
<li> 600 requests per minute.</li>
</ul>

<p>Customers exceeding this limit will receive error responses with a 429 response code.</p>

<table>
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794; width:40px">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
All <a href="#catalog">Catalog API endpoints</a> have a separate rate limit of <strong>100 requests per minute</strong> per integration (per account, not per access token) in addition to the global API limit.<br><br>
Exceeding this limit will result in a <strong>429 Too Many Requests</strong> response.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>Integrations that use Printify&#39;s API to create products and generate mockups have an additional daily limit. The
<a href="#publish-a-product">product publishing endpoint</a> has a limit of <strong>200 requests per 30 minutes</strong>, product
creation as a result of Order creation is not limited. If your application will require heavy usage of the Product
or Mockup generation functions, please <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/requests/new?ticket_form_id=4421334895377">create a support ticket</a> by selecting one of the topics on the support page and indicating &quot;API&quot; as the option chosen under &quot;Channels&quot;. Please add more information to provide full details and we will contact you shortly.</p>

<p>Requests resulting in an error response may not exceed 5% of your total requests.</p>

<p>We reserve the right to change or deprecate the APIs over time - we will provide developers ample notification in those
cases. These notifications will be sent to the email provided in your API settings.</p>
<h1 id='api-features'>API features</h1><h2 id='rest-api'>REST API</h2>
<p>Printify&#39;s REST API allows your application to manage a Printify shop on behalf of a Printify Merchant. Create products,
submit orders, and more...</p>

<p>Check out all available methods: <a href="#api-reference">API Reference</a></p>
<h2 id='webhooks-and-events'>Webhooks and Events</h2>
<p>Webhooks allow you to get an instant notification after an event occurrs in a Printify shop. </p>

<p>Send information to accounting right after an order was placed, send tracking to end customers as soon as it&#39;s
available, sync product descriptions, etc... - it&#39;s totally up to you.</p>

<p>More information:
<a href="#webhooks">Webhooks</a></p>
<h1 id='access-the-printify-api'>Access the Printify API</h1>
<p>You can access the Printify API as an individual merchant or as a platform. Both of them require different types of
authentication. Learn about each of them below.</p>
<h2 id='individual-accounts'>Individual Accounts</h2>
<p>Connect to a single Printify Merchant account and the shops that are a part of that account. Create products, submit
artwork, create and receive orders and more. Authentication is achieved through a Personal Access Token. </p>

<p>See more details in
<a href="#create-a-personal-access-token">Authentication</a>. </p>
<h2 id='platforms'>Platforms</h2>
<p>Connect applications that offer services to multiple merchants each with different Printify merchant accounts. Manage
orders for multiple Printify Merchants, offer merchants the option to sell on your platform, and more. Authentication is
achieved through OAuth 2.0</p>

<p>See more details in
<a href="#oauth-2-0">Authentication</a></p>
<h2 id='use-cases'>Use cases</h2><h3 id='create-orders-with-user-generated-content'>Create orders with user-generated content</h3>
<p>Regardless of whether you use your own mockup generator, or you capture user generated content. Through the Printify API
you can easily place those images on any products in our catalog, offer them for purchase, and fulfill.</p>
<h3 id='connect-your-own-e-commerce-channel'>Connect your own E-commerce channel</h3>
<p>Don&#39;t use Etsy, Shopify, Woocommerce, or any of our other available E-commerce solutions? Connect your own with the
Printify API. Enjoy the same benefits of automation that merchants using our existing integrations do.</p>
<h3 id='support-existing-integrations-with-more-functionality'>Support existing integrations with more functionality</h3>
<p>Already using one of our integrations such as Shopify or Woocommerce? Build any additional functionality you need and
connect via Printify API to continue to get all of your sales and order data in your existing shop.</p>
<h3 id='start-offering-merchandise-sales-to-your-community'>Start offering merchandise sales to your community</h3>
<p>Do you have an application or platform with an engaged community. Connect to the Printify API and easily start
monetizing your community by allowing them to sell Print on Demand merchandise through your platform. </p>
<h1 id='authentication'>Authentication</h1>
<p>The Printify platform provides two ways of integrating. You can integrate with a Personal Access Token that you can use
to manage a single Printify account, or you can integrate through OAuth 2.0 as a platform that will be managing multiple
Printify Merchant accounts.</p>

<p>Unless otherwise mentioned in the documentation for a specific endpoint, all endpoints support both OAuth 2.0 and
Personal Access Token.</p>
<h2 id='create-a-personal-access-token'>Create a personal access token</h2>
<p>A personal access token allows your application to connect to a single Printify Merchant account and the shops created within that account.</p>
<h4 id='step-1'>Step 1</h4>
<p>Before creating your personal access token, you will first need a Printify account. If you haven&#39;t created an account yet, <a href="https://printify.com/app/register">please do so here</a> and complete the onboarding procedure.</p>
<h4 id='step-2'>Step 2</h4>
<p>Now that you have your Printify account, navigate to My Profile, then Connections. In the Connections section you will be able to generate your Personal Access Tokens and set your Token Access Scopes. </p>
<h4 id='step-3'>Step 3</h4>
<p>You will be able to generate multiple tokens. Tokens can be set to have different Access Scopes. </p>

<p>Please note that for security purposes, this token will only be visible immediately after generating only. Please make sure you store it in a secure location.</p>

<p>Access tokens are valid for one year, they expire after that timeframe and you will need to generate a new one to replace it. If you lose your access token, you will also need to generate a new one. </p>

<p><a class="button" href="https://printify.com/app/account/api" target="_blank">Generate token</a></p>
<h4 id='step-4'>Step 4</h4>
<p>Once generated, you can use that token as credentials for API requests in place of a user name and password.</p>

<p>All requests must also specify a <em>User-Agent</em> header. The value of this header should either be the type of client, such
as &quot;NodeJS&quot; or &quot;PHP,&quot; or the name of your application.</p>

<p>After you have authenticated to the API, you can send requests to the API using any programming language or program that
can send HTTP requests. The base URL for all endpoints is <code><em>
<a href="https://api.printify.com/v1/">https://api.printify.com/v1/</a></em></code>.</p>

<p>Here is an example:</p>

<p><code>curl -X GET https://api.printify.com/v1/shops.json --header &quot;Authorization: Bearer $PRINTIFY_API_TOKEN&quot;</code></p>
<h4 id='step-5'>Step 5</h4>
<p>Once youve set the API up, go to your store by clicking on My Stores, then Add new store. You should see Shopify, Etsy, WooCommerce, and the new option, API. </p>

<p>Click connect to connect your store to Printify via the API.</p>
<h2 id='oauth-2-0'>OAuth 2.0</h2>
<p>Using OAuth 2.0 you will be able to offer your application to the growing community of Printify Merchants.</p>

<p>On this page:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#prerequisites">Prerequisites</a></li>
<li><a href="#connecting-your-app-to-printify">Connecting your app to Printify</a>

<ul>
<li><a href="#getting-grant-codes">Getting grant codes</a></li>
<li><a href="#getting-tokens">Getting tokens</a></li>
<li><a href="#refreshing-access-tokens">Refreshing access tokens</a></li>
<li><a href="#using-access-tokens">Using access tokens</a></li>
</ul></li>
<li><a href="#authentication-endpoints">Endpoints</a></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='prerequisites'>Prerequisites</h3>
<ol>
<li>Authentication for your integration starts with <a href="https://printify.typeform.com/to/sDrLZo">registering your app.</a> This
link takes you to an application form where you will answer some questions about your business, expected integration
timeline and your applications functionality. If your application is approved, you will receive instructions via
email for how to receive your app ID, and how to set the required
<a href="#access-scopes">access scopes</a> your application will need.</li>
<li>You&#39;ll use the app ID to initiate the OAuth handshake between Printify and your integration. </li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Note:</strong> Reviewing applications can take up to 1 week.</p>

<p><a class="button" href="https://printify.typeform.com/to/sDrLZo" target="_blank">Register your app</a></p>
<h3 id='connecting-your-app-to-printify'>Connecting your app to Printify</h3>
<p>There are 4 steps to connecting your integration to a Merchant&#39;s Printify account using OAuth:</p>

<ol>
<li>The Printify merchant will be presented with a screen that allows them to
<a href="#getting-grant-codes">grant access to your integration</a>.</li>
<li>After the Merchant grants access, they&#39;ll be returned to your app, with a code appended to the URL. Use that code and
your app ID to get an
<a href="#getting-tokens">access_token and refresh_token.</a></li>
<li>Use that access_token to
<a href="#using-access-tokens">authenticate any API calls</a> that you make for that Printify account.</li>
<li>Once that access_token expires, use the refresh_token from Step 2 to
<a href="#refreshing-access-tokens">generate a new access_token.</a></li>
</ol>
<h3 id='getting-grant-codes'>Getting grant codes</h3>
<p>Initiating OAuth access is the first step for having merchants grant your application access to their Printify account. In order to
initiate OAuth connection for your App, you&#39;ll first need to send a Printify merchant to an authorization page, where that
merchant will need to grant access to your app. When your app sends a merchant to that authorization page, you&#39;ll use
the query parameters detailed below to identify your app.</p>

<p>Merchants must be signed into Printify to grant access, so any user that is not logged into Printify will be directed to
a login screen before being directed back to the authorization page. The authorization screen will show the details of
your app.</p>

<p>Depending on whether or not the merchant grants access, they will be redirected to the accept_url or decline_url that you specified, if access was granted, a code query
parameter is appended to the URL and you&#39;ll use that code to get an access token from Printify.</p>
<h4 id='url-fields'>URL fields</h4>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
app_id
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">app_id=x</code>
The app ID provided to you after registering your app.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
accept_url
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">accept_url=x</code>
The URL that you want the visitor redirected to after granting access to your app. A code that can be used to exchange for tokens will be appended to the end of the URL.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
decline_url
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">decline_url=x</code>
The URL that you want the visitor redirected to after denying access to your app.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
state
<small class="recommended">RECOMMENDED</small>
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">state=123</code>
Persistent variable during connection flow.
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<table>
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
For security reasons, the accept and decline URL must use https in production. When testing using localhost, http can be used. Also, you must use a domain, as IP addresses are not supported.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<h3 id='getting-tokens'>Getting tokens</h3>
<p>Use the grant code you get after a user authorizes your app to exchange for an access token and refresh token. The access token will be
used to authenticate requests that your app makes. When you get the Access tokens, you also get expiration time
for the token. When token expires you have to use Refresh token to get a new Access token.</p>
<h4 id='request-parameters'>Request parameters</h4>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
app_id
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">app_id=x</code>
The app ID provided to you after registering your app.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
code
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">code=y</code>
The code parameter returned to your accept_url when the user authorized your app, it is returned by the GET /app/oauth/accept endpoint and passed back to the consumer app.
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<table>
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
Printify access tokens will fluctuate in size as we change the information that is encoded in the tokens. We recommend allowing for tokens to be up to 3,000 characters to account for any changes we may make.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<h3 id='refreshing-access-tokens'>Refreshing access tokens</h3>
<p>Use a previously obtained refresh token to generate a new access token. Access tokens expire after 6 hours, so if you
need offline access to data in Printify, you&#39;ll need to store the refresh token you get when initiating your OAuth
integration, and use that to generate a new access token once the initial access token expires.</p>
<h4 id='request-parameters-2'>Request parameters</h4>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
app_id
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">app_id=x</code>
The app ID provided to you after registering your app.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
refresh_token
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">refresh_token=x</code>
The refresh token returned by POST /app/oauth/tokens in the previous step.
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h3 id='using-access-tokens'>Using access tokens</h3>
<p>OAuth 2.0 access tokens are provided as a bearer token, in the Authorization http header.</p>

<p>The header format is: <code>Authorization: Bearer {token}</code></p>
<h3 id='endpoints'><a name="authentication-endpoints"></a> Endpoints</h3><h4 id='get-grant-code'>Get grant code</h4>
<p>This request is made to the base URL <code><em><a href="https://printify.com/">https://printify.com/</a></em></code>.</p>

<table>
<tr class="heading">
<td>GET</td>
<td>/app/authorize?{URL_fields}</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Authorization request</b><br/>

<small><strong>URL fields</strong></small>

<code class="multi language-json">
app_id=x
&accept_url=https://example.com
&decline_url=https://example.com
&state=123
</code>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Possible outcomes</b><br/>
<small><strong>If access is granted, a URL redirect will follow with a grant code appended to the url</strong></small>
<code class="multi language-json">
https://www.example.com/?code=aabbccxxeeaabbccxxeeaabbccxxee
</code>
<small><strong>If there are any problems with the authorization, error parameters will be received instead of the code</strong></small>
<code class="multi language-json">
https://www.example.com/?error=error_code
&error_description=Human%20readable%20description%20of%20the%20error
</code>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<h3 id='convert-grant-code-to-tokens'>Convert grant code to tokens</h3>
<p>Requests after authentication are made to the base URL <code><em><a href="https://api.printify.com/v1/">https://api.printify.com/v1/</a></em></code>.</p>

<table>
<tr class="heading">
<td>POST</td>
<td>/app/oauth/tokens</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Convert grant code to tokens</b><br/>

<small><strong>Request parameters</strong></small>

<code class="multi language-json">
app_id=x
&code=y
</code>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Possible responses</b><br/>
<small><strong>If successful, a JSON response with the tokens will be received</strong></small>
<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{
"access_token": "...",
"refresh_token": "...",
"expire_at": "2020-10-14 11:26:10+00:00"
}</code><br/>
<br/><small><strong>If there are any problems with the request, a 400 response will be received with an error message</strong></small>
<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{
"error": "error_code",
"error_description": "A human readable error message"
}</code>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<h3 id='refresh-access-token'>Refresh access token</h3>
<table>
<tr class="heading">
<td>POST</td>
<td>/app/oauth/tokens/refresh</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Refresh access token</b><br/>

<small><strong>Request parameters</strong></small>

<code class="multi language-json">
app_id=x
&refresh_token={from-the-get-tokens-request}
</code>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Possible responses</b><br/>
<small><strong>If successful, a JSON response with the tokens will be received</strong></small>
<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{
"access_token": "...",
"refresh_token": "...",
"expire_at": "2020-10-14 11:26:10+00:00"
}</code><br/>
<br/><small><strong>If there are any problems with the request, a 400 response will be received with an error message</strong></small>
<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{
"error": "error_code",
"error_description": "A human readable error message"
}</code>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<h1 id='v1-api-reference'>V1 API Reference</h1>
<p>The Printify API is organized around
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Representational_State_Transfer">REST</a>.</p>

<p>Our API has predictable resource-oriented URLs, accepts
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/POST_(HTTP)#Use_for_submitting_web_forms">form-encoded</a> request bodies, returns
<a href="http://www.json.org/">JSON-encoded</a> responses, and uses standard HTTP
<a href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7231#section-6.1">response codes</a>, authentication, and verbs.</p>

<p><a href="postman/printify_postman_collection.json" download>Download Postman Collection</a></p>
<h2 id='api-basics'>API basics</h2>
<ul>
<li>All requests are done via HTTPs. Requests via insecure HTTP are not supported.</li>
<li>Printify API works with UTF-8 encoded data. Please make sure everything you send over in API calls also uses UTF-8.</li>
<li>All data received from API and submitted to API is JSON, so the content type should be:
<code>application/json;charset=utf-8</code></li>
<li>Date/time values returned by Printify API are in UTC unless stated otherwise.</li>
<li>The base URL for all endpoints is
<code><em><a href="https://api.printify.com/v1/shops.json">https://api.printify.com/v1/</a></em></code>.</li>
<li><code>{variable}</code> in the URLs means you should substitute it with the proper variable value.</li>
<li>The API currently does not support CORS and requests from a frontend application will not be processed for
security reasons. You will need to set up a server-side application to access the API and ensure
secure storing of the API token.</li>
</ul>
<h2 id='api-pagination'>API pagination</h2>
<p>Besides the <code>data</code> property returned in response, there are also other properties that are helpful for paginating over the resources.</p>

<table>
<tr>
<td>
first_page_url
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"first_page_url": "/?page=1"</code>
URL for the first page of results - helpful in rewinding to the beginning of batch processing.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
prev_page_url
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"prev_page_url": "/?page=2"</code>
URL for the previous page of results - helpful in going back or iterating from the last resource.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
next_page_url
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"next_page_url": "/?page=4"</code>
URL for next page of results - helpful in iterating over results without doing page calculations.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
last_page_url
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"last_page_url": "/?page=5"</code>
URL for the last page of results - helpful in jumping to the end of results.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
current_page
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"current_page": 3</code>
Current page of results.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
last_page
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"last_page": 5</code>
Last page of results.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
total
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"total": 49</code>
The total number of results.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
per_page
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"per_page": 10</code>
The number of items retrieved in response.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
from
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"from": 21</code>
The ordinal number of first item in response.
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>
to
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"to": 30</code>
The ordinal number of last item in response.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<h2 id='shops'>Shops</h2>
<p>All product creation and order submission in a Printify Merchant&#39;s account happens through a shop. Merchant&#39;s can have
multiple shops in one Printify account. Each of these shops can be connected to different sales channels and each has
independent products, orders, and analytics.</p>

<p>On this page:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#what-you-can-do-with-the-shops-resource">What you can do with the shops resource</a></li>
<li><a href="#shop-properties">Shop properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#shops-endpoints">Endpoints</a></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='what-you-can-do-with-the-shops-resource'>What you can do with the shops resource</h3>
<p>The shops resource serves one purpose, it allows you to view the list of existing shops in a Printify account.</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-list-of-existing-shops">GET /v1/shops.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a list of existing shops in a Printify account</small></li>
<li><a href="#disconnect-a-shop">DELETE /v1/shops/{shop_id}/connection.json</a><br/><small>Disconnect a shop from a Printify account</small></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='shop-properties'>Shop properties</h3>

<small>READ-ONLY</small>

A unique int identifier for the shop. Each id is unique across the Printify system.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
title
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"title": "Shop's title"</code>
The name of the shop.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
sales_channel
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"sales_channel": "Sales channel name"</code>
The name of the associated sales channel. If none are connected it defaults to "disconnected".
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<h2 id='catalog'>Catalog</h2>
<p>Through the Catalog resource you can see all of the products, product variants, variant options and print providers
available in the Printify catalog.</p>

<p>Products in the Printify catalog are referred to as blueprints (only after user artwork has been added, are they referred to as products). </p>

<p>Every blueprint in the printify catalog has multiple Print Providers that offer that blueprint. In addition to general
differences between Print Providers including location and print technology employed, each Print Provider also offers
different colors, sizes, print areas and prices.</p>

<p>Each Print Provider&#39;s blueprint has specific size and color combinations known as variants. Variants also contain
information on a products available print areas and sizes.</p>

<p>On this page:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#what-you-can-do-with-the-catalog-resource">What you can do with the catalog resource</a></li>
<li><a href="#blueprint-properties">Blueprint properties</a>

<ul>
<li><a href="#print-provider-properties">Print provider properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#catalog-variant-properties">Variant properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#catalog-placeholder-properties">Placeholder properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#catalog-shipping-properties">Shipping properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#profile-properties">Profile properties</a></li>
</ul></li>
<li><a href="#catalog-endpoints">Endpoints</a></li>
<li><a href="#catalog-structure">Structure</a></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='what-you-can-do-with-the-catalog-resource'>What you can do with the catalog resource</h3>
<p>The Printify Public API lets you do the following with the Catalog resource:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-list-of-available-blueprints">GET /v1/catalog/blueprints.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a list of all available blueprints</small></li>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-specific-blueprint">GET /v1/catalog/blueprints/{blueprint_id}.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a specific blueprint</small></li>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-list-of-print-providers">GET /v1/catalog/blueprints/{blueprint_id}/print_providers.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a list of all print providers that fulfill orders for a specific blueprint</small></li>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-list-of-variants">GET /v1/catalog/blueprints/{blueprint_id}/print_providers/{print_provider_id}/variants.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a list of all variants of a blueprint from a specific print provider</small></li>
<li><a href="#retrieve-shipping-information">GET /v1/catalog/blueprints/{blueprint_id}/print_providers/{print_provider_id}/shipping.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve the shipping information for all variants of a blueprint from a specific print provider</small></li>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-list-of-available-print-providers">GET /v1/catalog/print_providers.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a list of all available print-providers</small></li>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-specific-print-provider">GET /v1/catalog/print_providers/{print_provider_id}.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a specific print-provider and a list of associated blueprint offerings</small></li>
</ul>

"print_on_side": "regular"
</code>
States the type of side print. possible values are "regular" for extending print area to the sides of canvas and "mirror" to keep original print area and mirror it to the sides.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
separator_type
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">
"separator_type": "Numbers"
</code>
Required with "separator_color" and specific to clock type blueprints, States the type clock separator. Possible string values are "Numbers" numeric separators, "Lines" for single bar separators, and "None" to specify that no separators be used.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
separator_color
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">
"separator_color": "#f100ff"
</code>
Required with "separator_type" and specific to clock type blueprints, States the type clock separator. Value must be a valid string hexadecimal color code.
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<h4 id='retrieve-a-list-of-variants-of-a-blueprint-from-a-specific-print-provider'><a id="retrieve-a-list-of-variants"></a> Retrieve a list of variants of a blueprint from a specific print provider</h4>
<table>

<tr class="heading">
<td>GET</td>
<td>/v1/catalog/blueprints/{blueprint_id}/print_providers/{print_provider_id}/variants.json</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
show-out-of-stock
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
Depending on the value, it shows all variants or only those not out of stock. Without passing this query param, the list will contain only those variants in stock.
<br>0 - show only variants that are in stock.
<br>1 - also show variants out of stock (all variants).
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Retrieve a list of variants of a blueprint from a specific print provider</b><br/>

<h3 id='structure'><a id="catalog-structure"></a> Structure</h3>
<p>Structure of Catalog resource with possible transitions between endpoints.</p>

<p><a href="images/CatalogStructure-f3350579.png"><img src="images/CatalogStructure-f3350579.png" alt="catalog structure" /></a> <br /></p>
<h2 id='products'>Products</h2>
<p>The Product resource lets you list, create, update, delete and publish products to a store.</p>

<p>On this page:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#what-you-can-do-with-the-product-resource">What you can do with the product resource</a></li>
<li><a href="#product-properties">Product properties</a>

<ul>
<li><a href="#product-variant-properties">Variant properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#product-placeholder-properties">Placeholder properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#image-properties">Image properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#image-pattern-properties">Image Pattern properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#mock-up-image-properties">Mock-up image properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#publishing-properties">Publishing properties</a></li>
</ul></li>
<li><a href="#products-endpoints">Endpoints</a></li>
<li><a href="#products-structure">Products Structure</a></li>
<li><a href="#image-positioning">Image positioning</a></li>
<li><a href="#products-common-error-cases">Common error cases</a></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='what-you-can-do-with-the-product-resource'>What you can do with the product resource</h3>
<p>The Printify Public API lets you do the following with the Product resource:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-list-of-products">GET /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a list of all products</small></li>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-product">GET /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a product</small></li>
<li><a href="#retrieve-product-gpsr-information">GET /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}/gpsr.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a product&#39;s GPSR information</small></li>
<li><a href="#create-a-new-product">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products.json</a><br/><small>Create a new product</small></li>
<li><a href="#update-a-product">PUT /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}.json</a><br/><small>Update a product</small></li>
<li><a href="#delete-a-product">DELETE /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}.json</a><br/><small>Delete a product</small></li>
<li><a href="#publish-a-product">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}/publish.json</a><br/><small>Publish a product</small></li>
<li><a href="#set-product-publish-status-to-succeeded">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}/publishing_succeeded.json</a><br/><small>Set product publish status to succeeded</small></li>
<li><a href="#set-product-publish-status-to-failed">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}/publishing_failed.json</a><br/><small>Set product publish status to failed</small></li>
<li><a href="#notify-that-a-product-has-been-unpublished">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}/unpublish.json</a><br/><small>Notify that a product has been unpublished</small></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='product-properties'>Product properties</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
id
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"id": "5cb87a8cd490a2ccb256cec4"</code>
A unique string identifier for the product. Each id is unique across the Printify system.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
title
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"title": "Product's title"</code>
The name of the product.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
description
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"description": "Product's description"</code>
A description of the product. Supports HTML formatting for compatible sales channels.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
safety_information
<small class="optional">OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"safety_information": "GPSR information: John Doe, <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="275342545367425f464a574b420944484a">[email&#160;protected]</a>, 123 Main St, Apt 1, New York, NY, 10001, US
Product information: Gildan, 5000, 2 year warranty in EU and UK as per Directive 1999/44/EC
Warnings, Hazzard: No warranty, US
Care instructions: Machine wash: warm (max 40C or 105F), Non-chlorine: bleach as needed, Tumble dry: medium, Do not iron, Do not dryclean",</code>
Safety information of the product. Can be retrieved using the GPSR endpoint. Supports HTML formatting for compatible sales channels.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
tags
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"tags": ["T-shirt", "Men's"]</code>
Tags are also published to sales channel.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
options
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"options": [{
"name": "Colors",
"type": "color",
"values": [{
"id": 751,
"title": "Solid White",
"colors": [
"#F9F9F9"
]
}]
}]</code>
Options are read only values and describes product options. There can be up to 3 options for a product.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
variants
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"variants": [{
"id": 123,
"price": 1000,
"title": "Solid Dark Gray / S",
"sku": "PRY-123",
"grams": 120,
"is_enabled": true,
"is_default": false,
"is_printify_express_eligible": true,
"options": [751, 2]
}]
</code>
A list of all product variants, each representing a different version of the product. But during product creation, only the variant id and price are necessary. See <a href="#variant-properties">variant properties</a> for reference.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
images
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"images": [{
"src": "http://example.com/tee.jpg",
"variant_ids": [123, 124],
"position": "front",
"is_default" : false,
}]</code>
Mock-up images are read only values. The mock-up images are grouped by variants and position. See <a href="#mock-up-image-properties">mock-up image properties</a> for reference.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
created_at
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"created_at": "2017-04-18 13:24:28+00:00"</code>
The date and time when a product was created.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
update_at
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"update_at": "2017-04-18 13:24:28+00:00"</code>
The date and time when a product was last updated.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
visible
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"visible": true</code>
Used for publishing. Visibility in sales channel. Can be <code>true</code> or <code>false</code>, defaults to <code>true</code>.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
blueprint_id
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"blueprint_id": 5</code>
Required when creating a product, but is read only after. See <a href="#catalog">catalog</a> for how to get <code>blueprint_id</code>.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
print_provider_id
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"print_provider_id": 5</code>
Required when creating a product, but is read only after. See <a href="#catalog">catalog</a> for how to get <code>print_provider_id</code>.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
user_id
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"user_id": 5</code>
User id that a product belongs to.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
shop_id
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"shop_id": 1</code>
Shop id that a product belongs to.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
print_areas
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"print_areas": [{
"variant_ids": [123, 124],
"placeholders": [{
"position": "front",
"images": []
}],
}]</code>
All print area values are required. Each variant has a print area attached to it. Each print area has placeholders which represent printable areas on a product. For example the front of the t-shirt, back of the t-shirt etc. Each placeholder has images and their positions, where they need to be printed in the printable area. See <a href="#product-placeholder-properties">placeholder properties</a> for reference.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
print_details
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">
"print_details": {
"print_on_side": "regular"
}
}]</code>
"print_on_side" key is used to set the type of side printing for canvases. There are three possible values:<br/>
<ul>
<li>"regular" - to extend print area to the sides of canvas</li>
<li>"mirror" - to keep original print area and mirror it to the sides</li>
<li>"off" - stop printing on sides</li>
</ul>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
external
<small>CONDITIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"external": [{
"id": "A123abceASd",
"handle": "/path/to/product",
"shipping_template_id": "B123abceASd"
}]</code>
Updated by sales channel with publishing succeeded endpoint. Id and handle are external references in the sales channel. See <a href="#set-product-publish-status-to-succeeded">publishing succeeded</a> endpoint for more reference.
<br>
Shipping Template ID is optional and can be passed during product creation or update.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
is_locked
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"is_locked": true</code>
A product is locked during publishing. Locked products can't be updated until unlocked.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
is_printify_express_eligible
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"is_printify_express_eligible": true</code>
Flag to indicate if product could be eligible for <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/9116968124689-Printify-Express-Delivery" target="_blank">Printify Express Delivery</a>, depending on selection of its variant.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
is_economy_shipping_eligible
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"is_economy_shipping_eligible": true</code>
Flag to indicate if product could be eligible for <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/22109518886161-Economy-Shipping" target="_blank">Economy Shipping</a>, depending on selection of its variant.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
is_printify_express_enabled
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"is_printify_express_enabled": true</code>
Flag to indicate if <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/9116968124689-Printify-Express-Delivery" target="_blank">Printify Express Delivery</a> is enabled for the product. Printify Express Delivery can be enabled only for eligible products (see <code>is_printify_express_eligible</code> flag). Defaults to <code>false</code>.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
is_economy_shipping_enabled
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"is_economy_shipping_enabled": true</code>
Flag to indicate if <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/22109518886161-Economy-Shipping" target="_blank">Economy Shipping</a> is enabled for the product. Economy Shipping can be enabled only for eligible products (see <code>is_economy_shipping_eligible</code> flag). Defaults to <code>false</code>.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
sales_channel_properties
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
Lists product properties specific to the sales channel associated with the product, if the sales channel has such custom properties, the attributes are listed in the object and may be actionable, but for all custom integrations, it will either be <font color="purple">null</font> or an empty array.
<br>
<strong>Amazon</strong>
<code class="multi language-json">"sales_channel_properties": {
"free_shipping": false,
"bullet_points": [
"Machine-washable",
"100% cotton"
],
"no_variation_parent": false,
"brand_name": "Some Amazon approved brand name that has been set on the Printify store"
}</code>
<strong>Etsy</strong>
<code class="multi language-json">"sales_channel_properties": {
"free_shipping": false,
"personalisation": [
{
"instructions": "Please provide the name you would like to be printed on the mug",
"buyer_response_limit": 30
}
]
}</code>
<strong>Big Commerce</strong>
<code class="multi language-json">"sales_channel_properties": {
"categories": [1, 2, 3],
"free_shipping": false
}</code>
<strong>eBay</strong>
<code class="multi language-json">"sales_channel_properties": {
"free_shipping": false
}</code>
<strong>Shopify</strong>
<code class="multi language-json">"sales_channel_properties": {
"collections": ["T-shirts", "Red Clothing"],
"free_shipping": false
}</code>
<strong>Squarespace</strong>
<code class="multi language-json">"sales_channel_properties": {
"store_page": "https://some-store.squarespace.com"
}</code>
<strong>TikTok</strong>
<code class="multi language-json">"sales_channel_properties": {
"delivery_service_id": "123",
"warehouse_id": "456",
"free_shipping": false,
"personalisation": "Personalisation instructions"
}</code>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
views
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"views": [
{
"id": 34395,
"label": "Front side",
"position": "front",
"files": [
{
"src": "https://images.printify.com/api/catalog/618e1792f80e2001a840687b.svg",
"variant_ids": [
76255
]
},
]
}
]</code>
Lists blank blueprint images with dedicated print areas. Each view has a label, position, and files source url for a list of variants.
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h3 id='variant-properties'><a id="product-variant-properties"></a> Variant properties</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
id
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"id": 123</code>
A unique int identifier for the product variant from the blueprint. Each id is unique across the Printify system. See catalog for instructions on how to get variant ids.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
sku
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"sku": "SKU-123"</code>
Optional unique string identifier for the product variant. If one is not provided, one will be generated by Printify.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
price
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"price": 1000</code>
Price in cents, integer value.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
cost
<small >READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"cost": 400</code>
Product variant's fulfillment cost in cents, integer value.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
title
<small >READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"title": "Solid Dark Gray / S"</code>
Variant title.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
grams
<small >READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"grams": 120</code>
Weight in grams for a product variant
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
is_enabled
<small >OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"is_enabled": true</code>
Used for publishing, the value is true if one has the variant in question selected as an offering and wants it published.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
is_default
<small >OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"is_default": true</code>
Only one variant can be default. Used when publishing to sales channel. Default variant's image will be the title image of the product.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
is_available
<small >READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"is_available": true</code>
Actual stock status of the variant, if false, the variant is out of stock and vice versa.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
is_printify_express_eligible
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"is_printify_express_eligible": true</code>
Flag to indicate if product's variant is eligible for <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/9116968124689-Printify-Express-Delivery" target="_blank">Printify Express</a> delivery.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
options
<small >READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"options": [751, 2]</code>
Reference to options by id.
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<h3 id='image-pattern-properties'>Image pattern properties</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
spacing_x
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"spacing_x": 0.5</code>
Float value. Horizontal Spacing expressed relative to width, where 0.5 would mean the item should repeat each half-width of image, and 1 means no spacing, 1.5 would mean 50% spacing etc.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
spacing_y
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"spacing_y": 0.5</code>
Float value. Vertical Spacing expressed relative to height, where 0.5 would mean the item should repeat each half-height of image, and 1 means no spacing, 1.5 would mean 50% spacing etc.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
angle
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"angle": 0</code>
Float value. Allows changing the axis along which items repeat. 0 means horizontal. Accepts values from -45 to +45 (Because the result of all other angles can already be achieved by staying within this range).
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
offset
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"offset": 0.5</code>
Float value. Allows specifying offset between 2 lines. Setting this to 0.5 will produce a "brick" pattern. Accepts values between -1 and 1.
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<tr>

Url of a mock-up image.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
variant_ids
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"variant_ids": [
61618,
61619,
61620,
61621,
61622
]</code>
Array of integer ids for variants illustrated by the mock-up image.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
position
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"position": "front"</code>
Camera position of a mockup (i.e. what part of the product is being displayed).
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
is_default
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"is_default": true</code>
Used by the sales channel. If set to <code>true</code>, The specific mockup is the title image. Can be used to decide the first image displayed when a product's page is accessed.
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h3 id='publishing-properties'>Publishing properties</h3>
<p>The &quot;publish&quot; button in the Printify app only locks the product on the Printify app and triggers the product:publish:started event if you are subscribed to it, see See <a href="#product-events">Product events</a> for reference. To publish a product, you need to create it manually on your store from the data you can obtain from the product resource or develop a system to automate that. Once done, you can use the <a href="#set-product-publish-status-to-succeeded">Publish succeeded endpoint</a> or <a href="#set-product-publish-status-to-failed">Publish failed endpoint</a> to unlock the product.</p>

<table>

<tr>
<td>
images
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"images": true</code>
Used by the sales channel. If set to <code>false</code>, Images will not be published, and existing images will be used instead.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
variants
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"variants": true</code>
Used by the sales channel. If set to <code>false</code>, product variations will not be published.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
title
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"title": true</code>
Used by sales channel. If set to <code>false</code>, product title will not be updated.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
description
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"description": true</code>
Used by sales channel. If set to <code>false</code>, product description will not be updated.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
tags
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"tags": true</code>
Used by sales channel. If set to <code>false</code>, product tags will not be updated.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
shipping_template
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"shipping_template": true</code>
Used by Etsy and Amazon sales channels only. If set to <code>false</code>, product shipping template will not be updated.
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<h4 id='update-a-product'>Update a product</h4>
<p>A product can be updated partially or as a whole document. When updating variants, all variants must be present in the request.</p>

<table>

<tr class="heading">
<td>PUT</td>
<td>/v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}.json</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Update a product</b><br/>

<code>PUT /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}.json</code><br/>

<code class="multi language-json">{
"title": "Product"
}</code>

<h4 id='publish-a-product'>Publish a product</h4>
<p>This does not implement any publishing action unless the Printify store is connected to one of our other supported sales channel integrations, if your store is custom and is subscribed to the product::pubish::started event, that event will be triggered and the properties that are set in the request body will be set in the event payload for your store to react to if implemented. The case is the same for attempting to publish a product from the Printify app. See <a href="#product-events">product events</a> for reference.</p>

<table>

<tr class="heading">
<td>POST</td>
<td>/v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}/publish.json</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Publish a product</b><br/>

<code>POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}/publish.json</code><br/>

<code class="multi language-json">{
"title": true,
"description": true,
"images": true,
"variants": true,
"tags": true,
"keyFeatures": true,
"shipping_template": true
}</code>

<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{}</code>
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h4 id='set-product-publish-status-to-succeeded'>Set product publish status to succeeded</h4>
<p>Using this endpoint removes the product from the locked status on the Printify app and sets the the it&#39;s external property with the handle you provide in the request body.</p>

<table>

<tr class="heading">
<td>POST</td>
<td>/v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}/publishing_succeeded.json</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Set product publish status to succeeded</b><br/>

<code>POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}/publishing_succeeded.json</code><br/>

<code class="multi language-json">{
"external": {
"id": "5941187eb8e7e37b3f0e62e5",
"handle": "https://example.com/path/to/product"
}
}</code>

<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{}</code>
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<h3 id='structure'><a id="products-structure"></a> Structure</h3>
<p>Structure of Product resource with possible transitions between endpoints.</p>

<p><a href="images/ProductsStructure-4217fa4a.png"><img src="images/ProductsStructure-4217fa4a.png" alt="products structure" /></a> <br /></p>
<h4 id='image-positioning'>Image positioning</h4>
<ul>
<li>Coordinate system <br />
<img class="t-shirt-image" src="images/PrintifyCoordinates-1e0f89a3.png" alt="coordinate system">
<br />
Printify uses the <code>[0,00; 0,00] .. [1,00; 1,00]</code> cartesian coordinate system, with the placeholder center being
<code>x=0,5</code>, <code>y=0,5</code>.</li>
<li>Artwork scale <br/>
<img class="t-shirt-image" src="images/PrintifyScaling100-800703b4.png" alt="scale 1,00">
<img class="t-shirt-image" src="images/PrintifyScaling50-64af13c5.png" alt="scale 0,5"></li>
</ul>

<p><br />
The scale of the image (width) relative to the print area placeholder (width).
Scale can be anything from <code>0,00</code> to infinity.</p>

<ul>
<li><code>1,00</code> - scale image to fill the print area fully </li>
<li><p><code>0,5</code> - scale image to fill 1/2 of the the print area</p>

<ul>
<li>Artwork angle - 360&deg; angle </li>
</ul></li>
</ul>

<p>Rule of thumb: if you use artwork with width equal to print area placeholder width, set scale to <code>1,00</code> and position it
at <code>x=0,5</code> <code>y=0,5</code> - your design will be horizontally and vertically aligned and fill all the print area fully.</p>

<h3 id='common-error-cases'><a id="products-common-error-cases"></a> Common error cases</h3>
<p>You may receive errors when trying to create or update a product. A common error is due failing dpi validation because the image is low quality. If this happens, you will receive a detailed error message similar to the one shown here. </p>

<table>
<tr class="heading">
<td>POST</td>
<td>/v1/shops/{shop_id}/products.json</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Common error cases</b><br/>
<code>POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products.json</code>
<br/><small>400 Image has low quality error example (See HTTP Status Codes below)</small>

<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{
"status": "error",
// Exact error codes and messages are subject to change.
"code": 8203,
"message": "Validation failed.",
"errors": {
"reason": "Image has low quality",
"code": 8203
}
}</code>
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<table>
<tr class="heading">
<td>PUT</td>
<td>/v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}.json</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">

<code>PUT /v1/shops/{shop_id}/products/{product_id}.json</code>

<h2 id='orders'>Orders</h2>
<p>The Printify APl lets your application manage orders in a Merchant&#39;s shop. You can submit orders for existing products in a merchant&#39;s shop, or you can create new products <b>on-the-fly</b> with every order, as in the case of merchandise created with customizable user-generated content.</p>

<table>
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
<b>On-the-fly</b> product creation is a time-consuming operation. To ensure reliability, please create products in advance to avoid timeouts.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>Ordering existing products or creating products with orders will require different line item entries so that should be kept in mind.</p>

<table>
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
By default, new stores have <strong>automatic order approval</strong> enabled (24 hours). If auto-approval is active, orders will be sent to production automatically once imported/created, without calling the <a href="#send-an-existing-order-to-production">Send to production</a> API endpoint.<br><br>
If you prefer to control when orders are sent to production:
<ol>
<li>Check each store's <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/articles/4483625253265-How-can-I-set-up-store-details-and-order-approval-settings">Order approval settings</a> and set them to <strong>Manual</strong> to avoid unintended production.</li>
<li>When ready, explicitly trigger production via the <a href="#send-an-existing-order-to-production">Send to production</a> endpoint.</li>
</ol>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>On this page:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#what-you-can-do-with-the-order-resource">What you can do with the order resource</a></li>

</ul></li>

<h3 id='what-you-can-do-with-the-order-resource'>What you can do with the order resource</h3>
<p>The Printify Public API lets you do the following with the Order resource:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-list-of-orders">GET /v1/shops/{shop_id}/orders.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a list of orders</small></li>
<li><a href="#get-order-details-by-id">GET /v1/shops/{shop_id}/orders/{order_id}.json</a><br/><small>Get order details by id</small></li>
<li><a href="#submit-an-order">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/orders.json</a><br/><small>Submit an order</small></li>
<li><a href="#submit-a-printify-express-order">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/express.json</a><br/><small>Submit a Printify Express order</small></li>
<li><a href="#send-an-existing-order-to-production">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/orders/{order_id}/send_to_production.json</a><br/><small>Send an existing order to production</small></li>
<li><a href="#calculate-the-shipping-cost-of-an-order">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/orders/shipping.json</a><br/><small>Calculate the shipping cost of an order</small></li>
<li><a href="#cancel-an-order">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/orders/{order_id}/cancel.json</a><br/><small>Cancel an unpaid order</small></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='order-properties'>Order properties</h3>

</td>
</tr>

}</code>

"quantity": 1,

</td>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
total_shipping
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>

Shipping price in cents, integer value.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
total_tax
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"total_tax": 0</code>
Tax cost in cents, integer value.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
status
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"status": "pending"</code>
<p>Production status of the entire order in string format, it can be any of the following:</p>
<table>
<tr>
<th>Status</th>
<th>Definition</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>pending</code></td>
<td>An order is created in the <code>pending</code> status. Orders should not stay in this status for a long time.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>on-hold</code></td>
<td>
<p>The order is ready to handle user actions. Users can edit orders in this status. The order gets this status at later stages for various reasons:</p>
<ul>
<li>Line items are discontinued during the order processing</li>
<li>Line items go out of stock during the order processing</li>
<li>The order contains items with shipping restricted line items</li>
</ul>
<p>User needs to take actions upon orders that got the status during the submission.</p>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>sending-to-production</code></td>
<td>Order is picked for sending to production. The status should be changed when the system receives updates from print providers.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>in-production</code></td>
<td>Order has been received by the print providers successfully. Print providers start the fulfillment process on their side.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>canceled</code></td>
<td>The order is canceled. No actions can be taken towards the order by the user.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>fulfilled</code></td>
<td>All line items are fulfilled by all print providers. The last status for successful order fulfillment.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>partially-fulfilled</code></td>
<td>At least one of the line items is fulfilled, but not all of them.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>payment-not-received</code></td>
<td>The order could not be charged during the submission in our system. It can be retried by the merchant. The order waits for merchant actions.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>has-issues</code></td>
<td>If an order encounters any issue during its lifecycle it will get this status. For instance, the shipping address is invalid.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>cost-calculation</code></td>
<td>Cost calculation is in progress.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>unfulfillable</code></td>
<td>Order cannot be fulfilled due to inventory or technical issues.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>sending_to_production_delegate</code></td>
<td>Order delegated for external production handling.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>sending_to_production_delegate_sync</code></td>
<td>Order delegated for synchronous production handling.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>source-check-failed</code></td>
<td>Source file validation failed.</td>
</tr>
</table>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
shipping_method
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"shipping_method": 1</code>
<p>Method of shipping selected for the order, "1" is for standard shipping and "2" is for <strike>express</strike> priority shipping, "3" is for <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/9116968124689-Printify-Express-Delivery" target="_blank">Printify Express</a> shipping and "4" is for <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/22109518886161-Economy-Shipping">Economy</a> shipping. Please note, that express order can only contain products eligible for express delivery. Similarly, economy order can only contain products eligible for economy delivery. More about shipping methods can be read here: <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/articles/4483626155409-What-are-Printify-s-shipping-options">Printify's shipping options</a></p>
<table>
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
Please be aware that Printify Express Delivery is using carriers that might not be supported by all sales channels (e.g. Amazon, Tik Tok).
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<table>
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
Please be aware that only the <a href="#product-properties">Product's</a> and the <a href="#product-variant-properties">Variant's</a> eligibility (<code>is_printify_express_eligible</code> flag) is taken into account. Eligible but disabled products (<code>is_printify_express_enabled</code> flag) can still be ordered with <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/9116968124689-Printify-Express-Delivery" target="_blank">Printify Express Delivery</a>.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<table>
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
Please be aware that shipping method 4 (<code>economy</code>) will not be usable when creating a product with an order. Therefore, for this shipping method the product must already exist before placing an order on it.
</td>
</tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>Property value should be decoded based on the following table:</p>
<table>
<tr>
<th>Code</th>
<th>Old version</th>
<th>Transitional version [active]</th>
<th>Final version</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>1</td>
<td>standard</td>
<th>standard</th>
<td>standard</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>express</td>
<th>express<br>priority</th>
<td>priority</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>3</td>
<td></td>
<th>printify_express</th>
<td>express</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>4</td>
<td>economy</td>
<th>economy</th>
<td>economy</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The <b>printify_express</b> is a new shipping option that will later in the future change its name to the <b>express</b>. Current <b>express</b> option will be renamed to the <b>priority</b> name.</p>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>

</td>

</td>
</tr>

<h3 id='line-item-properties'>Line item properties</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
product_id
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"product_id": "5b05842f3921c9547531758d"</code>
A unique string identifier for the product. Each id is unique across the Printify system.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
external_id
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"external_id": "abc-1234"</code>
Unique identifier of the line item from the external system. Preserved during replacements and routing.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
variant_id
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"variant_id": 17887</code>
A unique int identifier for the product variant from the blueprint. Each id is unique across the Printify system.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
quantity
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"quantity": 1</code>
Describes the number of said product ordered as an integer.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
print_provider_id
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"print_provider_id": 5</code>
A unique int identifier for the print provider. Each id is unique across the Printify system.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
cost
<small >READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"cost": 1050</code>
Product variant's fulfillment cost in cents, integer value.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
shipping_cost
<small >READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"shipping_cost": 400</code>
Product variant's shipment cost in cents, integer value.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
status
<small >READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"status": "in-production"</code>
<p>Specific line item fulfillment status:</p>
<table>
<tr>
<th>Status</th>
<th>Definition</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>on-hold</code></td>
<td>
<p>The item waits for user actions. Items get this status when:</p>
<ul>
<li>The order is created.</li>
<li>The order fails at one of the checks in the submission process.</li>
<li>The order fails with payments.</li>
</ul>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>in-production</code></td>
<td>Print provider received the item for production.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>sending-to-production</code></td>
<td>Says that the order is picked for sending to production. The status is changed once the system receives updates from print providers.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>has-issues</code></td>
<td>Line item encountered an issue during its lifecycle.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>fulfilled</code></td>
<td>The item is fulfilled by the print provider.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><code>canceled</code></td>
<td>The item is canceled.</td>
</tr>
</table>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
metadata
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"metadata": {
"title": "18K gold plated Necklace",
"price": 2200,
"variant_label": "Golden indigocoin",
"sku": "168699843",
"country": "United States"
}</code>
Other details about the specific product variant. See <a href="#line-item-metadata-properties">line item metadata properties</a> for reference.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
sent_to_production_at
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"sent_to_production_at": "2017-04-18 13:24:28+00:00"</code>
The date and time the product variant was sent to production. It is stored in ISO date format.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
fulfilled_at
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"fulfilled_at": "2017-04-18 13:24:28+00:00"</code>
The date and time the product variant was fulfilled. It is stored in ISO date format.
</td>
</tr>

<h3 id='order-submission-properties'>Order submission properties</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
external_id
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"external_id": "2750e210-39bb-11e9-a503-452618153e4a"</code>
A unique string identifier from the sales channel specifying the order name or id.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
label
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"label": "000012"</code>
Optional value to specify order label instead of using "external_id"
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
line_items
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"line_items": [{
"product_id": "5bfd0b66a342bcc9b5563216",
"variant_id": 17887,
"quantity": 1,
"external_id": "line-item-abc-001"
}]</code>
Required for ordering existing products. Provide the product_id (Printify Product ID), variant_id (selected variant, e.g. 'White / XXL') and desired item quantity. If creating a product from the order is required, then additional attributes will need to be provided, specifically the blueprint_id and print_areas.
<code class="multi language-json">"line_items": [{
"print_provider_id": 5,
"blueprint_id": 9,
"variant_id": 17887,
"print_areas": {
"front": "https://images.example.com/image.png"
},
"quantity": 1,
"external_id": "line-item-abc-001"
}]</code>
See <a href="#product-properties">product properties</a> and <a href="#product-variant-properties">variant properties</a> for reference. Also, see <a href="#print-area-properties">print area properties</a> for reference on print_areas for product creation during order submission. It is also possible to order existing products by providing the product variant's SKU alone.
<code class="multi language-json">"line_items": [{
"sku": "MY-SKU",
"quantity": 1,
"external_id": "line-item-abc-001"
}]</code>
See <a href="#product-variant-properties">variant properties</a> for reference.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
shipping_method
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"shipping_method": 1</code>
Required to specify what method of shipping is desired, "1" means standard shipping, "2" means priority shipping, "3" means printify express shipping and "4" means economy shipping. It is stored as an integer.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
send_shipping_notification
<small class="boolean">BOOLEAN</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"send_shipping_notification": false</code>
A boolean for choosing whether or not to receive email notifications after an order is shipped.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
address_to
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"address_to": {
"first_name": "John",
"last_name": "Smith",
"email": "<a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="1e7b667f736e727b5e736d70307d7173">[email&#160;protected]</a>",
"phone": "0574 69 21 90",
"country": "BE",
"region": "",
"address1": "ExampleBaan 121",
"address2": "45",
"city": "Retie",
"zip": "2470"
}</code>
The delivery details of the order's recipient.
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h3 id='print-area-properties'>Print area properties</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
placeholder position and image url
<small class="required">REQUIRED</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"print_areas": {
"front": "https://images.example.com/image.png",
"back": "https://images.example.com/image.png"
}</code>
Required for creating products during order submission, See <a href="#placeholder-properties">placeholder properties</a> for reference.
Instead of specifing the url, it is also possible to provide an array with image objects that have additional keys for the advanced positioning:
<code class="multi language-json">
"print_areas": {
"front": [
{
"src": "https://images.example.com/image.png",
"scale": 0.15,
"x": 0.80,
"y": 0.34,
"angle": 215
},
{
"src": "https://images.example.com/image2.png",
"scale": 1,
"x": 0.5,
"y": 0.5,
"angle": 0
}
],
"back": [
{
"src": "https://images.example.com/image3.png",
"scale": 1,
"x": 0.5,
"y": 0.5,
"angle": 0
}
]
}
</code>
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h3 id='print-details-properties'>Print details properties</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
Special print options
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">
"print_details": {
"print_on_side": "mirror"
}
</code>
Used to store properties for special cases like printing on canvas sides or clock separators, See <a href="#print-details-properties">print details properties</a> for reference.
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h3 id='endpoints'><a id="orders-endpoints"></a> Endpoints</h3><h4 id='retrieve-a-list-of-orders'>Retrieve a list of orders</h4>
<table>

<tr class="heading">
<td>GET</td>
<td>/v1/shops/{shop_id}/orders.json</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
limit
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
<div>
Results per page<br/>
(default: 10, maximum: 10)
</div>
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
page
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
Paginate through list of results
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
status
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
Filter results by order status
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
sku
<small>OPTIONAL</small>
</td>
<td>
Filter results by product SKU - response will contain only those orders that have at least one product with passed SKU
</td>
</tr>

<h4 id='submit-a-printify-express-order'>Submit a Printify Express order</h4>
<table>

<tr class="heading">
<td>POST</td>
<td>/v1/shops/{shop_id}/orders/express.json</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Order an existing product with Printify Express Delivery</b><br/>

<p>
This API method creates one or two separate orders using the following logic:
<ol>
<li>If <strong>none</strong> of the line items are Printify Express eligible: one order with <code>"fulfilment_type": "ordinary"</code></li>
<li>If <strong>all</strong> of the line items are Printify Express eligible: one order with <code>"fulfilment_type": "express"</code></li>
<li>If at least one line item is Printify Express eligible, and at least one isn't: two separate orders, one <code>express</code>, and one <code>ordinary</code></li>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
Read more about Printify Express Delivery in <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/9116968124689-Printify-Express-Delivery" target="_blank">a dedicated Help center section</a>.
</p>

<table style="width: 100%">
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#bce4ff;width:7%;">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#bce4ff;text-align:left;">
<code>address_to.email</code> and <code>address_to.phone</code> fields are required for Printify Express eligibility.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<table style="width: 100%">
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794;width:7%;">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794;text-align:left;">
<p>The endpoint works only with already existing products.</p>

<p>Please be aware that Printify Express Delivery is using carriers that might not be supported by all sales channels (e.g. Amazon, Tik Tok).</p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<table style="width: 100%">
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794;width:7%;">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794;text-align:left;">
<p>Please be aware that only the <a href="#product-properties">Product's</a> and the <a href="#product-variant-properties">Variant's</a> eligibility (<code>is_printify_express_eligible</code> flag) is taken into account. Eligible but disabled products (<code>is_printify_express_enabled</code> flag) can still be ordered with <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/9116968124689-Printify-Express-Delivery" target="_blank">Printify Express Delivery</a>.</p>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<code>POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/orders/express.json</code><br/>

<code class="multi language-json">{

"variant_id": 17887,

"external_id": "line-item-abc-001"
},{
"sku": "MY-SKU",
"quantity": 1,
"external_id": "line-item-abc-001"
}],
"address_to": {
"first_name": "John",
"last_name": "Smith",
"email": "<a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection" class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="e5809d8488958980a588968bcb868a88">[email&#160;protected]</a>",
"phone": "0574 69 21 90",
"country": "BE",
"region": "",
"address1": "ExampleBaan 121",
"address2": "45",
"city": "Retie",
"zip": "2470"
}
}
</code>

<p>Response</p>
<code class="multi language-json">
{
"standard": 1000,
"express": 5000,
"priority": 5000,
"printify_express": 799,
"economy": 399
}
</code>
<p>Response contains the shipping options that are defined in the following table:</p>
<table>
<tr>
<th>Code</th>
<th>Old version</th>
<th>Transitional version [active]</th>
<th>Final version</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>1</td>
<td>standard</td>
<th>standard</th>
<td>standard</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>2</td>
<td>express</td>
<th>express<br>priority</th>
<td>priority</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>3</td>
<td></td>
<th>printify_express</th>
<td>express</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>4</td>
<td>economy</td>
<th>economy</th>
<td>economy</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>The <b>printify_express</b> is a new shipping option that will later in the future change its name to the <b>express</b>. Current <b>express</b> option will be renamed to the <b>priority</b> name.</p>
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<h2 id='uploads'>Uploads</h2>
<p>Artwork added to a Printify Product can be saved in the Media library to be reused on additional products.</p>

<p>You can use this API to directly add files to the media library, and later use image IDs when creating or modifying
products.</p>

<p>On this page:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#what-you-can-do-with-the-uploads-resource">What you can do with the uploads resource</a></li>
<li><a href="#uploads-image-properties">Image properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#uploads-endpoints">Endpoints</a></li>
<li><a href="#uploads-structure">Structure</a></li>
<li><a href="#uploads-common-error-cases">Common Error cases</a></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='what-you-can-do-with-the-uploads-resource'>What you can do with the uploads resource</h3>
<p>The Printify Public API lets you do the following with the Uploads resource:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-list-of-uploaded-images">GET /v1/uploads.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a list of uploaded images</small></li>
<li><a href="#retrieve-an-uploaded-image-by-id">GET /v1/uploads/{image_id}.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve an uploaded image by id</small></li>
<li><a href="#upload-an-image">POST /v1/uploads/images.json</a><br/><small>Upload an image</small></li>
<li><a href="#archive-an-uploaded-image">POST /v1/uploads/{image_id}/archive.json</a><br/><small>Archive an uploaded image</small></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='image-properties'><a id="uploads-image-properties"></a> Image properties</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
id
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"id": "5e16d66791287a0006e522b2"</code>
A unique string identifier for the image. Each id is unique across the Printify system.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
file_name
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"file_name": "Image's file name"</code>
The file name of the image.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
height
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"height": 5979</code>
The height of the image in pixels.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
width
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"width": 17045</code>
The width of the image in pixels.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
size
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"size": 1138575</code>
The file size of the image in bytes.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
mime_type
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"mime_type": "image/png"</code>
The media type of the image file.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
preview_url
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"preview_url": "https://example.com/artwork"</code>
A url to preview the image.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
upload_time
<small>READ-ONLY</small>
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"upload_time": "2020-01-09 07:29:43"</code>
The date and time the image was uploaded in ISO date format.
</td>
</tr>

</table>
