<h4 id='upload-an-image'>Upload an image</h4>
<p>Upload image files either via image URL or image file base64-encoded contents. The file will be stored in the Merchant&#39;s account
Media Library.</p>

<table>
<tr>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
<span>&#9888;</span>
</td>
<td style="background-color:#ffc794">
We highly recommend using upload via image URL for files larger than 5MB.<br>
Upload via image URL is the future-proof solution, as we plan to drop support for base64-encoded content uploads larger than 5MB in the future.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<table>

<tr class="heading">
<td>POST</td>
<td>/v1/uploads/images.json</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="3">
<b>Upload image to a Printify account's media library</b><br/>

<code>POST /v1/uploads/images.json</code>
<small>Body parameter (upload image by URL)</small>

<code class="multi language-json">{
"file_name": "1x1-ff00007f.png",
"url": "http://png-pixel.com/1x1-ff00007f.png"
}</code>

<small>Body parameter (upload image by base64-encoded contents)</small>

<code class="multi language-json">{
"file_name": "image.png",
"contents": "base-64-encoded-content"
}</code>

<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{
"id": "5941187eb8e7e37b3f0e62e5",
"file_name": "image.png",
"height": 200,
"width": 400,
"size": 1021,
"mime_type": "image/png",
"preview_url": "https://example.com/image-storage/uuid3",
"upload_time": "2020-01-09 07:29:43"
}</code>
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<h3 id='common-error-cases'><a id="uploads-common-error-cases"></a> Common Error cases</h3>
<p>When uploading images to the library, you may encounter errors. These are commonly due to download errors, incorrect file formats, or your image being too large. If these are the case, you will receive messages similar to these outlined here.</p>

<table>
<tr class="heading">
<td>POST</td>
<td>/v1/uploads/images.json</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<b>Common error cases</b><br/>
<code>POST /v1/uploads/images.json</code>
<small>400 Image download error example (See HTTP Status Codes below)</small>

<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{
"status": "error",
// Exact error codes and messages are subject to change.
"code": 10300,
"message": "Operation failed.",
"errors": {
"reason": "cURL error 6: Could not resolve host: png1-pixel.com",
"code": 10300
}
}</code><br/>

<br/><small>400 Image too large error example (See HTTP Status Codes below)</small>

<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{
"status": "error",
// Exact error codes and messages are subject to change.
"code": 8201,
"message": "Validation failed.",
"errors": {
"reason": "Failed to upload image. Cause: {\"code\":\"error.file.size.limit.exceeded\"}",
"code": 8201
}
}</code><br/>

<br/><small>400 Unsupported file format error example (See HTTP Status Codes below)</small>

<a href="#" class="code-toggle" data-text="Hide Response">View Response</a>
<code class="multi language-json hidden">{
"status": "error",
// Exact error codes and messages are subject to change.
"code": 8201,
"message": "Validation failed.",
"errors": {
"reason": "Failed to upload image. Cause: {\"code\":\"error.file.wrong.format\"}",
"code": 8201
}
}</code>
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h2 id='events'>Events</h2>
<p>Events are generated by some resources when certain actions are completed, such as the creation of a product, the fulfillment of an order. By requesting events, your app can know when certain actions have occurred in the shop.</p>

<p>On this page:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#shop-events">Shop events</a></li>
<li><a href="#product-events">Product events</a></li>
<li><a href="#order-events">Order events</a></li>
<li><a href="#event-properties">Event properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#resource-properties">Resource properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#resource-data-examples">Resource data examples</a>

<ul>
<li><a href="#shop-resource-data-examples">Shop resource data examples</a></li>
<li><a href="#product-resource-data-examples">Product resource data examples</a></li>
<li><a href="#order-resource-data-examples">Order resource data examples</a></li>
</ul></li>
<li><a href="#payload-examples">Payload examples</a></li>
</ul>

<tr>

id
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"id": "653b6be8-2ff7-4ab5-a7a6-6889a8b3bbf5"</code>

</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
type
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"type": "order:created"</code>
The type of event that occurred. Different resources generate different types of event.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
created_at
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"created_at": "2017-04-18 13:24:28+00:00"</code>
The date and time when the event was triggered.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
resource
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"resource": {
"id": "653b6be8-2ff7-4ab5-a7a6-6889a8b3bbf5",
"type": "product",
"data": {
"shop_id": 1234567,
"reason": "Request timed out"
}
}</code>
Information about the resource that triggered the event. Check <a href="#resource-properties">Resource properties</a> for reference.
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h3 id='resource-properties'>Resource properties</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
id
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"id": "5cb87a8cd490a2ccb256cec4"</code>
A unique string identifier for the resource. Each id is unique across the Printify system.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
type
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"type": "product"</code>
Resource type, currently valid types are <code>shop</code>, <code>product</code> and <code>order</code>.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
data
</td>
<td>
<code class="multi language-json">"data": {
"shop_id": 1234567,
"reason": "Request timed out"
}</code>
For more information see <a href="#resource-data-examples">Resource data examples</a>.
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h3 id='resource-data-examples'>Resource data examples</h3><h3 id='shop-events-2'><a id="shop-resource-data-examples"></a> Shop events</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
<code>shop:disconnected</code>
</td>
<td>
No resource data is sent.
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h3 id='product-events-2'><a id="product-resource-data-examples"></a> Product events</h3>
<table>

<tr>
<td>
<code>product:deleted</code>
</td>
<td>
No resource data is sent.
</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td>
<code>product:publish:started</code>
</td>
<td>
The values for the action property determine the resource data payload, the values can be "create", "update", or "delete". For "create" and "update" actions, the payload is as follows:
<code class="multi language-json">"data": {
"shop_id": 1234567,
"publish_details": {

},

}</code>

For reference on what other properties mean, check <a href="#publishing-properties">Publishing properties</a>.

<h2 id='webhooks'>Webhooks</h2>
<p>You can use webhook subscriptions to receive notifications about particular events in a shop. After you&#39;ve subscribed to a webhook, you can let your app execute code immediately after specific events occur in shops that have your app connected, instead of having to make API calls periodically to check their status. For example, you can rely on webhooks to trigger an action in your app when a merchant creates a new product in a store. By using webhooks subscriptions you can make fewer API calls overall, which makes sure that your apps are more efficient and update quickly. For more information what actually gets sent by a webhook check <a href="#event-properties">Event properties</a> and <a href="#resource-data-examples">Resource data examples</a>.</p>

<p>On this page:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#webhook-rules-to-follow">Webhook rules to follow</a></li>
<li><a href="#what-you-can-do-with-the-webhooks-resource">What you can do with the webhooks resource</a></li>
<li><a href="#webhook-properties">Webhook properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#webhook-endpoints">Webhook endpoints</a></li>
<li><a href="#securing-your-webhooks">Securing your Webhooks</a></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='webhook-rules-to-follow'>Webhook rules to follow</h3>
<p>To ensure that your webhook works correctly, follow these good practices:</p>

<ul>
<li>Printify will send a POST request to the URL you specify when the event occurs. </li>
<li>This POST request will contain a JSON payload with information about the event. </li>
<li>The expected response is a <strong>200 OK</strong>.</li>
<li>In case of a 4xx or 5xx response, Printify will retry the request up to 3 times, after which the webhook will be <strong>blocked</strong> for 1 hour.</li>
<li>If the webhook is blocked, no new requests will be sent to the URL until the block is lifted.</li>
</ul>
<h3 id='what-you-can-do-with-the-webhooks-resource'>What you can do with the Webhooks resource</h3>
<p>The Printify Public API lets you do the following with the Webhook resource:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#retrieve-a-list-of-webhooks">GET /v1/shops/{shop_id}/webhooks.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve a list of webhooks</small></li>
<li><a href="#create-a-new-webhook">POST /v1/shops/{shop_id}/webhooks.json</a><br/><small>Create a new webhook</small></li>
<li><a href="#modify-a-webhook">PUT /v1/shops/{shop_id}/webhooks/{webhook_id}.json</a><br/><small>Modify a webhook</small></li>
<li><a href="#delete-a-webhook">DELETE /v1/shops/{shop_id}/webhooks/{webhook_id}.json</a><br/><small>Delete a webhook</small></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='webhook-properties'>Webhook properties</h3>

<h3 id='securing-your-webhooks'>Securing your Webhooks</h3>
<p>Once your server is configured to receive payloads, it&#39;ll listen for any payload sent to the endpoint you configured.
For security reasons, you probably want to limit requests to those coming from Printify.</p>

<p>There are a few ways to go about this
- for example, you could opt to whitelist requests from Printify&#39;s IP address
- but a far easier method is to set up a secret token and validate the information. </p>

<p>Summary: </p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#setting-your-shared-secret-with-printify">Setting your shared secret with Printify</a></li>
<li><a href="#accessing-the-secret-from-your-backend">Accessing the Secret from your backend</a></li>
<li><a href="#validating-payloads-from-printify">Validating payloads from Printify</a></li>
</ul>
<h4 id='setting-your-shared-secret-with-printify'>Setting your shared secret with Printify</h4>
<p>You can generate the secret by running &#39;<code>openssl rand -hex 20</code>&#39;.</p>

<p>When your secret token is set, Printify will use it to create a hash signature with each payload body. Printify uses an HMAC
hexdigest to compute the hash <code>sha256</code> signature with your provided secret. </p>

<table>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<small>Secret example</small>
<code class="multi language-json">
7afa37fd47d7a52ea644382e04962a83c16aef62
</code>
</td>
</tr>

</table>

<p>This payload body signature is passed along with each request in the headers as <code>X-Pfy-Signature</code>. The signature format is: <code>sha256={digest}</code>.</p>

<table>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<small>Signature example</small>
<code class="multi language-json">
x-pfy-signature: sha256=4260d30ec4ee2a17181ae5072c846d8dfcb5ceb195e24de055fd9a21d8c6648f
</code>
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h4 id='accessing-the-secret-from-your-backend'>Accessing the Secret from your backend</h4>
<p>Next, set up a <code>SECRET_TOKEN</code> environment variable on your server that stores this token. <strong>Never hardcode the
secret into your app!</strong></p>

<table>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<small>Setting the SECRET_TOKEN environment variable example</small>
<code class="multi language-json">
$ export SECRET_TOKEN=your_token
</code>
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h4 id='validating-payloads-from-printify'>Validating payloads from Printify</h4>
<p>Next, compute a request body hash using your <code>SECRET_TOKEN</code>, and ensure that the hash from Printify matches. Printify
uses an HMAC hexdigest to compute the hash. <strong>Always use &quot;constant time&quot; string comparisons, which renders it safe from
certain timing attacks against regular equality operators.</strong></p>

<table>

<tr>
<td colspan="2">
<small>Validation sample (python)</small>
<code class="multi language-json">
import os
import hmac
def sha256hash(request):
hash = hmac.new(os.environ['SECRET_TOKEN'].encode('utf-8'),
request.data.encode('utf-8'),
'sha256')
return 'sha256=' + hash.hexdigest()
def secure_compare(a, b):
return hmac.compare_digest(a, b)
print('%r' % secure_compare(request.headers['x-pfy-signature'],
sha256hash(request)))
</code>
</td>
</tr>

</table>
<h1 id='v2-api-reference'>V2 API Reference</h1>
<p>The second version of the API is organized around the <a href="https://jsonapi.org/">JSON:API</a> specification. This version of the API is designed to be more consistent and predictable, and to provide a better foundation for future improvements. It follows JSON API standard on pagination, linking and can support the filtering if it is mentioned in the endpoint documentation.</p>

<p>New features and improvements are being added to the V2 API, and we encourage you to use it for new integrations. The V1 API will continue to be supported, but new features will only be added to the V2 API.</p>

<p>The V2 API is available at the following base URL: <code>https://api.printify.com/v2/</code>.</p>

<p>The <a href="https://help.printify.com/hc/en-us/sections/22109518886161-Economy-Shipping">Economy Shipping</a> costs listing is available only in the V2 API.</p>
<h2 id='catalog-v2'>Catalog V2</h2>
<p>Through the Catalog resource you can see all of the products, product variants, variant options and print providers
available in the Printify catalog.</p>

<p>Products in the Printify catalog are referred to as blueprints (only after user artwork has been added, they are referred to as products).</p>

<p>Every blueprint in the Printify catalog has multiple Print Providers that offer that blueprint. In addition to general
differences between Print Providers including location and print technology employed, each Print Provider also offers
different colors, sizes, print areas and prices.</p>

<p>Each Print Provider&#39;s blueprint has specific option (e.g. color, size) combinations known as variants. Variants also contain
information on a products&#39; available print areas and sizes.</p>

<p>On this page:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#v2-what-you-can-do-with-the-catalog-resource">What you can do with the catalog resource</a></li>
<li><a href="#v2-catalog-shipping-attributes">Shipping properties</a></li>
<li><a href="#v2-catalog-endpoints">Endpoints</a></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='what-you-can-do-with-the-catalog-resource'><a href="#v2-what-you-can-do-with-the-catalog-resource" id="v2-what-you-can-do-with-the-catalog-resource"></a> What you can do with the catalog resource</h3>
<p>The Printify Public API lets you do the following with the Catalog resource:</p>

<ul>
<li><a href="#v2-catalog-endpoints">GET /v2/catalog/blueprints/{blueprint_id}/print_providers/{print_provider_id}/shipping.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve the list of available shipping for all variants of a blueprint from a specific print provider</small></li>
<li><a href="#v2-catalog-endpoints">GET /v2/catalog/blueprints/{blueprint_id}/print_providers/{print_provider_id}/shipping/standard.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve the standard shipping handling time and shipping costs for all variants of a blueprint from a specific print provider.</small></li>
<li><a href="#v2-catalog-endpoints">GET /v2/catalog/blueprints/{blueprint_id}/print_providers/{print_provider_id}/shipping/priority.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve the priority shipping handling time and shipping costs for all variants of a blueprint from a specific print provider.</small></li>
<li><a href="#v2-catalog-endpoints">GET /v2/catalog/blueprints/{blueprint_id}/print_providers/{print_provider_id}/shipping/express.json</a><small>Retrieve the express shipping handling time and shipping costs for all variants of a blueprint from a specific print provider.</small></li>
<li><a href="#v2-catalog-endpoints">GET /v2/catalog/blueprints/{blueprint_id}/print_providers/{print_provider_id}/shipping/economy.json</a><br/><small>Retrieve the economy shipping handling time and shipping costs for all variants of a blueprint from a specific print provider.</small></li>
</ul>
<h3 id='shipping-list-attributes'><a href="#v2-catalog-shipping-propertiese" id="v2-catalog-shipping-attributes"></a> Shipping list attributes</h3>

"currency": "USD"
}</code>
Shipping cost for first, and potentially additional items. Returned in cents (1/100), for example: 399 = $3.99.
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<h1 id='http-status-codes'>HTTP Status Codes</h1>
<p>Printify API relies heavily on standard <a href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7231#section-6.1">HTTP response codes</a> codes.
Please find the brief summary of status codes used below.</p>
<h3 id='success'>Success</h3>
<table><thead>
<tr>
<th>Code</th>
<th>Name</th>
<th>Description</th>
</tr>
</thead><tbody>
<tr>
<td>200</td>
<td>OK</td>
<td>Request completed successfully.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>201</td>
<td>Created</td>
<td>The request has been fulfilled and has resulted in one or more new resources being created.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>202</td>
<td>Accepted</td>
<td>The request has been accepted for processing, but the processing has not been completed.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>204</td>
<td>No Content</td>
<td>Indicates that the server has successfully fulfilled the request and that there is no content to send in the response payload body.</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
<h3 id='user-error-codes'>User error codes</h3>
<p>These errors generally indicate a problem on the client side. If you are getting one of these, check your code and the
request details.</p>

<table><thead>
<tr>
<th>Code</th>
<th>Name</th>
<th>Description</th>
</tr>
</thead><tbody>
<tr>
<td>400</td>
<td>Bad Request</td>
<td>The request encoding is invalid; the request can&#39;t be parsed as a valid JSON.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>401</td>
<td>Unauthorized</td>
<td>Accessing a protected resource without authorization or with invalid credentials.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>402</td>
<td>Payment Required</td>
<td>The account associated with the API key making requests hits a quota that can be increased by upgrading the Printify API account plan.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>403</td>
<td>Forbidden</td>
<td>Accessing a protected resource with API credentials that don&#39;t have access to that resource.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>404</td>
<td>Not Found</td>
<td>Route or resource is not found. This error is returned when the request hits an undefined route, or if the resource doesn&#39;t exist (e.g. has been deleted).</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>413</td>
<td>Request Entity Too Large</td>
<td>The request exceeded the maximum allowed payload size. You shouldn&#39;t encounter this under normal use.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>422</td>
<td>Invalid Request</td>
<td>The request data is invalid. This includes most of the base-specific validations. You will receive a detailed error message and code pointing to the exact issue.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>429</td>
<td>Too Many Requests</td>
<td>Too Many Requests response status code indicates you have sent too many requests in a given amount of time (&quot;rate limiting&quot;).</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
<h3 id='server-error-codes'>Server error codes</h3>
<p>These errors generally represent an error on our side. In the event of a 5xx error code, detailed information about the
error will be automatically recorded, and Printify&#39;s developers will be notified.</p>

<table><thead>
<tr>
<th>Code</th>
<th>Name</th>
<th>Description</th>
</tr>
</thead><tbody>
<tr>
<td>500</td>
<td>Internal Server Error</td>
<td>The server encountered an unexpected condition.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>502</td>
<td>Bad Gateway</td>
<td>Printify&#39;s servers are restarting or an unexpected outage is in progress. You should generally not receive this error, and requests are safe to retry.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>503</td>
<td>Service Unavailable</td>
<td>The server could not process your request in time. The server could be temporarily unavailable, or it could have timed out processing your request. You should retry the request with backoffs.</td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>

<li>Last update Oct 3 2024 - lowered products max pagination from 100 to 50. </li>
</ul>
